{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":27591,"record_hash":"sha256:c8a8f7bff5d34b7012cfd02ead492f52e7b1c6285d53be03f2d1a35bab9e323f","timestamp":"2026-05-11T12:08:00.329Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"Yeah, this is the right question. Tool calls/results are useful, but they are also where the transcript stops being “conversation” and starts becoming “execution log.”\n\n**For session handoff**\n\nPros of keeping tool calls:\n- The next agent can see what was already tried: commands run, files inspected, tests executed.\n- Helps avoid repeating expensive exploration.\n- Gives concrete grounding beyond “the assistant said it checked X.”\n\nPros of keeping tool results:\n- The next agent can see actual evidence: test failures, compiler errors, command output, file snippets.\n- Very useful when no code was written yet but the agent has gathered context.\n\nCons:\n- Tool results dominate storage.\n- Raw command output can be noisy, repetitive, and sometimes sensitive.\n- Tool output may be less portable across machines, especially absolute paths, local env details, terminal noise.\n- If the future handoff agent receives too much tool output, it may drown in stale detail.\n\n**For PR/session review**\n\nPros of keeping tool calls:\n- Reviewers can see whether the agent did serious work: ran tests, inspected relevant files, searched docs, applied patches.\n- Tool names/commands are useful as a lightweight audit trail.\n\nPros of keeping tool results:\n- Useful proof for “tests passed/failed,” compiler output, benchmark output, etc.\n- Helps evaluate whether prompting was careful or just vibes.\n\nCons:\n- Full outputs are often too verbose for a web review view.\n- Most command output is not worth showing unless it is a failure, a test summary, or directly referenced in the conversation.\n- Large results make storage and UI slower, while adding little review value.\n\nMy recommendation for the POC: keep `tool_call`, but make `tool_result` much more selective or summarized later.\n\nA pragmatic storage shape now could be:\n\n| Kind | Store? | Shape |\n|---|---|---|\n| `message` | Yes | Full normalized text plus redacted source record |\n| `tool_call` | Yes | tool name + redacted input/command, probably no duplicated source fields |\n| `tool_result` | Maybe slim | tool name + exit/status + capped text, or only store failures/errors |\n| `session` | No transcript row | metadata only |\n| `other` | No | skip |\n\nIf we want to stay very small right now, I’d do this:\n\n```text\nStore only message + tool_call + tool_result.\nFor tool_result text, cap stored text to a reasonable size.\nSkip session + other transcript rows.\nPrune copied text/tool_input from source_record.\n```\n\nThat preserves the direction for both future use cases but avoids making GitMeta a full terminal log archive.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-11T12:08:00.329Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}